-- ── Coroot ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Coroot is an open-source, eBPF-based observability platform that auto-collects metrics, logs, traces, and profiles for Kubernetes without code instrumentation.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium (free Community Edition + per-core paid tiers)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (Community Edition)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2021, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$2-10 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Palo Alto, California, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Coroot: Open-Source eBPF Observability for Kubernetes$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Coroot is an open-source, eBPF-powered observability platform offering zero-instrumentation monitoring, service maps, SLO tracking, and AI root cause analysis.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Coroot is an open-source observability platform that uses eBPF, a Linux kernel technology for safely running sandboxed programs inside the kernel, to collect metrics, logs, traces, and continuous profiles from applications automatically, without requiring developers to add instrumentation code, SDKs, or agents inside their services. The company was founded in 2021 and is headquartered in Palo Alto, California, by a founding team that includes Anton Petruhin, Nikolay Sivko, and Peter Zaitsev, the latter also known as a co-founder of Percona, giving the team significant prior experience in open-source database and infrastructure tooling. Coroot is released under the Apache 2.0 license, with its full source code published and available for self-hosting.

The core technical premise of Coroot is that most observability tooling requires substantial manual setup: instrumenting code with tracing libraries, configuring log shippers, defining custom metrics, and building dashboards by hand. By using eBPF to observe network calls, system calls, and process behavior directly at the kernel level, Coroot can automatically construct a real-time service map of an application's architecture, detect anomalies, and correlate signals across metrics, logs, traces, and profiles without any code changes. This zero-instrumentation approach is particularly well-suited to Kubernetes environments, where Coroot can be deployed as a node-level agent (typically a DaemonSet) that observes every container on a node without requiring each service owner to separately configure observability. Alongside eBPF-based monitoring, Coroot includes service-level objective (SLO) tracking, smart alerting integrated with Slack, PagerDuty, and Microsoft Teams, deployment tracking to correlate releases with performance changes, cloud cost monitoring, continuous profiling for performance troubleshooting, and an AI-powered root cause analysis feature that helps engineers move directly from an anomaly to a likely explanation rather than manually correlating dashboards.

Coroot's licensing and pricing model follows an open-core structure. The Community Edition is fully open source, self-hosted, and free to use indefinitely, including for production clusters, which the company positions as full-featured Kubernetes observability free forever for development and smaller production environments. Above the free tier, Coroot offers a Standard paid edition priced at $1 per monitored CPU core per month, with volume discounts at scale and explicitly no separate charges based on data volume, a pricing model designed to contrast with usage-based observability vendors like Datadog or New Relic, where log and trace ingestion volume can drive costs up unpredictably. A 10-node cluster with 4 vCPUs per node, for example, would cost roughly $40 per month under the Standard plan. The Standard tier adds SSO, role-based access control (RBAC), and business-hours support to the Community Edition's feature set. A Premium tier, priced through direct sales contact, adds 24/7 support, phone support, premium onboarding, capacity planning assistance, air-gapped installation support for regulated or disconnected environments, and included team training, targeting larger enterprises with stricter support and compliance requirements. A 14-day trial is available for the paid tiers.

Coroot's target users are platform engineering, SRE, and DevOps teams operating Kubernetes clusters who want deep observability without either the operational burden of assembling and maintaining a full open-source stack (Prometheus, Grafana, Loki, Tempo, Pyroscope, etc. wired together manually) or the unpredictable, often steep costs of commercial SaaS observability platforms. Because eBPF-based monitoring avoids per-service instrumentation, Coroot is especially attractive to teams with polyglot service fleets, where instrumenting every language and framework with tracing SDKs would otherwise be a significant and ongoing engineering cost.

Coroot's competitive landscape includes both commercial APM/observability vendors, such as Datadog, New Relic, Dynatrace, Grafana Cloud, and Dash0, and other eBPF-native or open-source observability tools such as Pixie, SigNoz, and Groundcover. Coroot explicitly publishes comparison pages against several of these competitors, including Dash0 and SigNoz, positioning itself around three main differentiators: true zero-instrumentation setup via eBPF, self-hosted deployment that keeps telemetry data inside the customer's own infrastructure, and cost predictability through per-core rather than per-gigabyte-of-data pricing. As a company founded in 2021 with a small team, reported at roughly two to ten employees, Coroot is considerably smaller and younger than incumbents like Datadog or New Relic, and its plugin and integration ecosystem is correspondingly narrower, but its open-source distribution model and free Community Edition have made it a common recommendation within the Kubernetes and platform-engineering community for teams that want to avoid vendor lock-in and unpredictable observability bills. It is best understood as a Kubernetes-native, cost-conscious alternative to both hand-assembled open-source observability stacks and expensive commercial SaaS APM platforms. Because Coroot's Community Edition has no artificial feature caps on core monitoring capability, many teams start on the free self-hosted tier purely to evaluate eBPF-based observability before deciding whether the Standard tier's SSO, RBAC, and support terms justify the added per-core cost, which gives Coroot a lower-friction evaluation path than most enterprise observability vendors that gate core functionality behind a sales call. Coroot's dashboards present findings in plain language rather than raw metric queries where possible, aiming to make root-cause analysis accessible to engineers who are not observability specialists, which is a deliberate design choice given that many of its target customers are small platform teams without a dedicated observability or SRE function.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '883b2808-6d12-4830-b483-eca7281f59f1';

