-- ── Corteza ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Corteza is a 100% open-source low-code platform for building CRM, workflow automation, and enterprise messaging apps — a free, self-hosted alternative to Salesforce.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source (self-hosted); optional paid support from Planet Crust$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2019, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$~16 employees (Planet Crust, maker of Corteza)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Cork, Ireland$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Corteza: Open-Source Low-Code Platform (Salesforce Alt.)$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Corteza is a 100% open-source low-code platform with built-in CRM, workflow automation, and enterprise messaging — a free, self-hosted Salesforce alternative.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Corteza is a 100% open-source low-code development platform designed to let organizations build and iterate on CRM systems, structured business-process applications, and workflow automation quickly, while also connecting to nearly any external data source. Every piece of Corteza's code is published and reviewable on GitHub, and the project is released under the Apache 2.0 license, meaning it can be freely used, modified, self-hosted, and redistributed, including for commercial purposes, without licensing fees. Corteza is developed and maintained by Planet Crust, a company founded in 2019 and headquartered in Cork, Ireland (with earlier roots as Crust Technology before rebranding), which continues to build the open-source project while offering paid support, consulting, and managed-hosting services around it. Reported figures place Planet Crust at roughly sixteen employees, positioning it as a small, focused open-source company rather than a large enterprise software vendor.

Architecturally, Corteza is composed of three integrated core components that together aim to replicate much of the functionality found in Salesforce's platform. Corteza Low Code is the platform's foundational low-code application builder, providing an intuitive drag-and-drop interface for creating record-based, structured data applications, comparable to Salesforce's Lightning Platform. Corteza CRM is a feature-rich, ready-made customer relationship management application built on top of that low-code layer, giving organizations a 360-degree view of leads, accounts, and deals, along with lead scoring, sales forecasting, and a built-in automation module for tasks like assigning leads or triggering follow-up communications. Corteza Messaging is an enterprise collaboration and communication tool comparable to Slack or Salesforce Chatter, providing secure, high-performance messaging for teams working inside the platform. Together, these components form what Corteza documentation describes as a Unified Workspace, conceptually similar to Google Workspace but centered on structured business data and workflow rather than documents and email. Under the hood, Corteza's backend is written in Go (Golang), chosen for performance and straightforward deployment as compiled binaries or containers, while its frontend is built with Vue.js, and the platform exposes a REST API along with webhook support for integrating external systems and building custom automation on top of the low-code data model.

Because Corteza has no licensing fees and no per-user pricing, its cost model differs fundamentally from commercial low-code and CRM platforms like Salesforce, Microsoft Power Platform, or OutSystems, all of which charge substantial per-seat subscription fees that scale with organization size. Organizations that self-host Corteza pay only for their own infrastructure (servers, storage, and the DevOps effort required to deploy and maintain it via Docker or Kubernetes), and can optionally purchase support, custom development, or managed hosting directly from Planet Crust for organizations that prefer not to run the platform entirely in-house. This makes Corteza particularly attractive to organizations that are cost-sensitive at scale, want to avoid vendor lock-in tied to a proprietary data model, or operate under data-residency or sovereignty requirements that make self-hosting preferable to a multi-tenant SaaS platform.

Corteza's most direct point of comparison, repeatedly emphasized in its own marketing, is Salesforce: the project explicitly positions itself as an open-source Salesforce alternative, with Corteza CRM mapped conceptually against Salesforce Sales Cloud, Corteza Low Code against Salesforce's Lightning Platform, and Corteza Messaging against Salesforce Chatter. Beyond Salesforce, Corteza also competes in the broader open-source and low-code CRM space against platforms like SuiteCRM, EspoCRM, and Odoo's CRM module, as well as against low-code application platforms such as Appsmith, Budibase, and ToolJet, though Corteza's combination of CRM, messaging, and a general-purpose low-code builder in one unified codebase is somewhat distinctive among these alternatives, most of which specialize in either CRM or general application building rather than both.

Corteza's target users span two overlapping groups: organizations seeking a free, self-hosted alternative to Salesforce for CRM and business-process needs, and developers who want an open-source low-code foundation for building custom, record-based internal applications beyond CRM, anything from project tracking systems to case management tools, without starting from scratch or committing to a proprietary platform. The trade-off organizations make in choosing Corteza is largely one of ecosystem maturity versus cost and control: Corteza's third-party integration marketplace, UI polish, and community size are smaller than those of well-funded commercial competitors, and self-hosting requires in-house or contracted DevOps capability, but in exchange, organizations gain a fully auditable, license-fee-free platform they can run entirely under their own infrastructure and data-governance policies. Planet Crust also publishes app templates and pre-built solution accelerators on top of Corteza's low-code engine, covering use cases such as project management and case management, which lets adopters start from a working application rather than an empty low-code canvas, shortening the time needed to reach a usable CRM or business-process app compared with building entirely from scratch. Documentation for Corteza is maintained at docs.cortezaproject.org, separate from Planet Crust's commercial marketing site, reflecting the project's dual identity as both an independently governed open-source codebase and a commercially supported product, a structure common among open-core companies that want to keep community contribution processes clearly separated from paid support and services offerings.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '925db15a-65f7-4d4f-bb9d-cd05222b869f';

