-- ── Corteza CRM ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Corteza CRM is the open-source customer relationship management module of the Corteza low-code platform, offering lead, account, and deal tracking for free.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source (self-hosted); optional paid support from Planet Crust$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2019, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$~16 employees (Planet Crust, maker of Corteza)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Cork, Ireland$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Corteza CRM: Free, Open-Source CRM Software$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Corteza CRM is a free, open-source customer relationship management app built on the Corteza low-code platform, with leads, deals, and automation.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Corteza CRM is the customer relationship management application built on top of Corteza, the 100% open-source low-code platform maintained by Planet Crust, a company founded in 2019 and headquartered in Cork, Ireland. While Corteza as a whole is a general-purpose low-code platform that also includes an application builder and enterprise messaging tool, Corteza CRM is specifically the ready-made CRM application that ships with it, comparable in scope to Salesforce Sales Cloud, but distributed as free, open-source, self-hosted software under the Apache 2.0 license rather than as a paid SaaS subscription.

Functionally, Corteza CRM gives organizations a 360-degree overview of leads and accounts, combining contact management, lead and deal tracking, communication history logging, and task and calendar management in a single application. It includes sales-oriented features such as lead scoring to help prioritize which prospects sales teams should pursue first, sales forecasting to project pipeline outcomes, and personalized quote generation. Reporting and analytics capabilities let teams view real-time graphs and metrics on pipeline health and conversion rates to support data-driven sales decisions. A distinguishing feature of Corteza CRM relative to many CRM products is its built-in automation module, which lets organizations automate CRM processes such as ranking incoming leads, automatically assigning contacts to the appropriate sales rep, and triggering communications like sending brochures or follow-up emails, all configured through the platform's workflow tools rather than requiring custom code.

Because Corteza CRM is built on top of Corteza's underlying low-code engine, it is not a rigid, fixed-schema CRM in the way many commercial products are. Organizations can use Corteza's low-code tools to customize the CRM's data model, fields, forms, and workflows to match their specific sales process, rather than being limited to a vendor-defined structure. This is functionally similar to how Salesforce's Sales Cloud can be extensively customized using the Lightning Platform, except that in Corteza's case, both the CRM application and the customization layer underneath it are open source and free to modify. The application is delivered as part of the same Go-backend, Vue.js-frontend Corteza codebase, and exposes the same REST API and webhook capabilities as the broader platform, allowing Corteza CRM to be integrated with external marketing automation, email, or support tools.

On pricing, Corteza CRM carries no licensing fees. Organizations self-host it (typically via Docker or Kubernetes) and pay only for their own infrastructure, with Planet Crust offering optional paid support, implementation consulting, and managed hosting for organizations that would rather not run the deployment entirely in-house. This is a fundamentally different cost structure from mainstream CRM SaaS products such as Salesforce, HubSpot, or Zoho CRM, which charge recurring per-seat subscription fees that scale directly with the number of sales reps using the system. For small and mid-sized organizations with technical staff capable of self-hosting, this can represent a substantial ongoing cost saving, particularly as sales team headcount grows and per-seat SaaS pricing would otherwise scale linearly.

Corteza CRM's target users are organizations that want CRM functionality without recurring per-seat licensing costs, that have concerns about vendor lock-in or data residency with SaaS CRM providers, or that need a level of customization beyond what off-the-shelf commercial CRMs typically allow without expensive platform add-ons. It competes most directly with other open-source CRM options such as SuiteCRM, EspoCRM, and Odoo's CRM module, and, for organizations evaluating it as a Salesforce replacement specifically, with Salesforce Sales Cloud itself, albeit at zero licensing cost in exchange for the responsibility of self-hosting and maintaining the platform. Compared to standalone open-source CRMs, Corteza CRM's differentiator is that it inherits the full extensibility of the broader Corteza low-code platform, so organizations that outgrow the default CRM feature set can extend or reshape it using the same low-code tools rather than needing a separate development framework. The trade-off, as with Corteza generally, is a smaller support community, fewer prebuilt third-party integrations, and less UI polish relative to well-funded, venture-backed commercial CRM vendors, along with the operational responsibility of self-hosting unless an organization opts into Planet Crust's paid hosting and support services. Because it inherits Corteza's Apache 2.0 licensing, Corteza CRM can also be embedded or resold by systems integrators building vertical CRM solutions for specific industries, a use case less common with proprietary CRM platforms whose licensing terms typically restrict redistribution or white-labeling without a separate reseller agreement.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '016aac11-14a9-4e56-958c-3b361e5b1ef4';

