-- ── CosmoLex ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$CosmoLex is cloud-based legal practice management software combining trust/IOLTA accounting, billing, time tracking, and document management for law firms.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription (per-user/month)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$89/user/month (billed annually)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2013, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Small-to-mid size; part of ProfitSolv$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Knoxville, Tennessee, USA (ProfitSolv parent company)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$CosmoLex: Cloud Legal Practice Management & Trust Accounting$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$CosmoLex is cloud-based legal practice management software with built-in trust and business accounting, billing, time tracking, and document management.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$CosmoLex is cloud-based legal practice management software built specifically for law firms, integrating trust and business accounting, time tracking, billing, email and document management, and task and calendar management into a single web-based application. It was founded in 2013 by Rakesh Kabra, with the founding team recognizing as early as 2012 that the legal industry was shifting toward cloud-based tools and that cloud technology could streamline legal practice operations while being especially cost-efficient for small and mid-sized law firms compared to traditional on-premise practice-management software. In 2018, CosmoLex was acquired by Tabs3 Software, a longstanding legal technology company, as part of an effort to expand Tabs3's cloud-based offerings. CosmoLex now operates as part of ProfitSolv, a portfolio company headquartered in Knoxville, Tennessee, founded in 2020, that owns and operates a collection of software solutions aimed at professional services firms, including legal, accounting, and other billable-hours-driven practices.

The defining architectural characteristic of CosmoLex, and its primary market differentiator, is that it is built as a fully integrated accounting and practice-management system rather than a practice-management tool that connects to a separate accounting product. Most competing legal practice management platforms, such as Clio or MyCase, handle case management, billing, and time tracking natively but require an external integration with QuickBooks or a similar accounting package to produce full financial statements and general ledger accounting. CosmoLex instead includes a built-in general ledger, full double-entry business accounting, and trust accounting in the same system used for matter management, eliminating the need for firms to reconcile data between two separate applications. This is particularly significant for trust accounting (also called IOLTA accounting in the United States), which is subject to strict state bar compliance rules governing how client funds held in trust must be tracked, reconciled, and reported; CosmoLex's trust accounting module is built specifically to enforce these compliance requirements, including three-way reconciliation between the trust ledger, bank statement, and client ledger balances, which helps reduce the risk of inadvertent commingling or misuse of client funds that can trigger bar disciplinary action.

Beyond accounting, CosmoLex includes matter and case management with custom fields and templates, conflict-of-interest checking to flag potential representation conflicts before a new matter is opened, calendaring and task management with dependent task and event logic (available on higher tiers), customizable views for tracking firm data, a native mobile app, integrated document management, and online payment processing through credit card, debit card, and eCheck via its CosmoLexPay add-on. The platform is entirely cloud-based and accessed through a browser at law.cosmolex.com, requiring no local software installation, which appeals particularly to solo practitioners and small firms without in-house IT staff.

CosmoLex's pricing is structured around three main tiers, Standard, Elite, and Elite plus Website, priced per user per month, with the company's own marketing indicating a base rate around $89 per user per month when billed annually (or approximately $99 per user per month billed monthly), and the Elite tier adding features such as a matter status board, matter workflows with status automation, dependent task and event logic, and matter budgets. Add-on products extend the core platform: CosmoLex CRM is available for around $147 per month billed annually (or $177 per month billed month-to-month) for up to three users, and CosmoLex Websites, a website-building and hosting add-on for law firms, is priced around $149 per month annually or $159 per month billed monthly. A 10-day free trial with full functionality (with some limitations, such as a single bank feed connection) is available for firms evaluating the platform before subscribing.

CosmoLex's target customers are solo practitioners and small to mid-sized law firms, particularly those that want to consolidate practice management and accounting into a single subscription rather than paying for and integrating two separate systems. Its competitors include Clio, MyCase, PracticePanther, Smokeball, and Filevine in the broader legal practice management category, with CosmoLex's built-in accounting and trust compliance functionality serving as its primary point of differentiation against Clio and MyCase in particular, both of which rely on third-party accounting integrations rather than native general ledger accounting. For firms that specifically prioritize eliminating separate bookkeeping software and want built-in trust accounting compliance tooling, CosmoLex is frequently recommended by legal technology reviewers as one of the strongest options in its category, while firms that already have an established accounting workflow or prefer best-of-breed tools for each function may find competitors with deeper integration marketplaces a better fit. CosmoLex's acquisition by Tabs3 and subsequent integration into the ProfitSolv portfolio has not changed its core product identity as a standalone, browser-based practice management suite; rather, it has given CosmoLex access to a broader base of legal-vertical software expertise and cross-sell opportunities with other ProfitSolv products serving law firms and other professional services businesses.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'cee2123f-c1f7-4345-90bb-fd1586f42fd7';

